 keep</h2>\n\n<p>Keep the following paperwork:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your child’s Unique Reference Number - this is shown on the voucher </li>\n  <li>the statements for the account</li>\n  <li>details of the type of account and the provider</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This will make it easier if you need to query anything or make any changes to the account.</p>\n\n<h2>Changing accounts or providers</h2>\n\n<p>Check if the current provider offers the type of account you want to change to. If they don&rsquo;t, you may need to try another provider.</p>\n\n<p>To change provider, you need to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>choose a new provider</li>\n  <li>contact the new provider to check what forms you need to fill in</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The new provider will get in touch with your existing account provider to arrange for the money to be moved. They will also tell HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) about the change.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>From April 2013, new providers will no longer tell <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> about account changes.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Changing a registered contact</h2>\n\n<p>You can change the registered contact if your family circumstances have changed.</p>\n\n<p>Follow these steps:</p>\n\n<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Get an application form from the provider.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Both you - and the person who wants to be the new registered contact - sign the form.</p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Return the form to the provider.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Only someone with parental responsibility for the child can be the registered contact, like a parent, step-parent or legal guardian.</p>\n\n<p>If you split up from someone who is the registered contact and want to take this role on instead, both of you will need to agree to this.</p>\n\n<h2>When your child is 16 or 18</h2>\n\n<p>When your child is 16 they can take over the account and manage it. When they&rsquo;re 18, they can take the money out.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>A child can still choose to let their registered contact manage the account when they turn 16.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-trust-funds/adding-money-to-the-account","slug":"adding-money-to-the-account","order":7,"title":"Adding money to the account","body":"<p>Anyone can pay money into a Child Trust Fund (<abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr>) account.</p>\n\n<h2>How much you can add</h2>\n\n<p>You can put £3,600 a year into the account - the start date for the year is the child&rsquo;s birthday and the end date is the day before their next birthday. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If the £3,600 limit isn’t used in a year, you can’t carry any unused amount forward to the following year to make up the difference.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How to pay money in</h2>\n\n<p>For stakeholder accounts you can add money by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>cheque</li>\n  <li>standing order</li>\n  <li>direct debit</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>For savings or share accounts, check with your provider.</p>\n\n<h2>Government payments</h2>\n\n<p>Payments made by the government don&rsquo;t count towards the £3,600, apart from:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>payments made by the Welsh government up to 31 January 2011</li>\n  <li>payments made by a local council to a child they are looking after</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>The year you open the account</h2>\n\n<p>There are different rules for the first year. The start date is the day the account is opened but the end date is still the day before the child&rsquo;s next birthday. </p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-trust-funds/if-your-child-is-terminally-ill-or-dies","slug":"if-your-child-is-terminally-ill-or-dies","order":8,"title":"If your child is terminally ill or dies","body":"<p>You can take money out of your child&rsquo;s Child Trust Fund (<abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr>) account if they are terminally ill. If your child has died, the money passes to whoever inherits the child&rsquo;s estate (their property and possessions). </p>\n\n<h2>If your child is terminally ill</h2>\n\n<p>&lsquo;Terminally ill&rsquo; means that they have a disease or illness that is going to get worse and are likely to die within 6 months. Only the registered contact can take money out.</p>\n\n<h3>How to take money out</h3>\n\n<p>Contact the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> Helpline to let them know that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your child is terminally ill</li>\n  <li>you want to take the money out of the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> account </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You’ll need to provide evidence that your child is terminally ill.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>If your child is already getting <a href=\"/dla-disability-living-allowance-benefit\" title=\"Disability Living Allowance (DLA)\">Disability Living Allowance (<abbr title=\"Disability Living Allowance\">DLA</abbr>)</a> because of their illness, tell the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> Helpline when you contact them.</p>\n\n<p>If your child doesn’t get <abbr title=\"Disability Living Allowance\">DLA</abbr>, the <abbr title=\"Child Trust Fund\">CTF</abbr> office will send you a form for your doctor to complete and return to them.</p>\n\n<h2>If your child dies</h2>\n\n<p>The money in the account will be paid to the person who inherits the child&rsquo;s estate. This is often one of the child’s parents, but if your child was married, it could be their husband or wife.</p>\n\n<p>If you weren&rsquo;t able to open the account before your child died, HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) will still pay you what your child was entitled to. </p>\n\n<p>If you get <a href=\"/changes-affect-child-benefit\" title=\"Child benefit if a child dies\">Child Benefit</a> for a child who has died this can still carry on for a short time. It may also help with any extra costs you fac